explanation:
For deciding whether any lines in OS_SocketOpen_Impl are unreachable you must know the concrete set of values and compiled-in code paths the switches and macros can actually produce: 

- OS_stream_internal_record_t: determines the exact type of stream->socket_type and stream->socket_domain fields (e.g. whether they are enums, bitfields, or other types) and thus whether other values are possible at runtime.

- OS_impl_file_internal_record_t: shows the layout/fields (e.g. impl->fd) so you can confirm assignments/uses are valid and whether the struct or its accessors could introduce control flow that affects reachability.

- OS_SocketType (all enumerators, specifically OS_SocketType_DATAGRAM and OS_SocketType_STREAM and any other enumerators): required to check whether the switch over socket_type covers every enumerator. If every enumerator is covered, the default branch may be provably unreachable; if there are additional enumerators, the default may be reachable.

- OS_SocketDomain (all enumerators, specifically OS_SocketDomain_INET and OS_SocketDomain_INET6 and any others): same reason as above for the domain switch — you must know the full enumerator set to determine if the default case can occur.

- OS_NETWORK_SUPPORTS_IPV6 (preprocessor symbol): whether the INET6 case is compiled in depends on this macro. If it is defined the switch covers INET6 too; if not defined then the domain switch covers fewer values and the default may be reachable. This is a compile-time determinant of reachable code.

- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET macro: this macro expands to the table lookup / token-to-object code (it may call OS_ObjectIndexFromToken). You need its definition/semantics to determine whether stream and impl pointers can be NULL, whether the macro can trap, assert or longjmp, or whether it constrains the possible values stored in the returned records (affecting reachability of later branches).

- OS_stream_table and OS_impl_filehandle_table: the object tables referenced by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET — their type/contents and any index constraints may limit what socket_type/socket_domain values can appear for a valid token, affecting whether switch defaults are reachable.

- OS_IMPL_SET_SOCKET_FLAGS macro: it is invoked near the end; if this macro contains additional control-flow (returns, goto, longjmp-like behavior) it can make subsequent lines unreachable or otherwise change the control-flow graph used to decide unreachable code. Even if it does not, its content may be relevant to whether some code paths are effectively no-ops or terminate early.

(Other symbols such as socket/setsockopt and the OS_* return-code constants do not affect which source lines are ever selected by the switch/default constructs or the compile-time inclusion of cases, so they are not required to decide the unreachable-code question for the switches and defaults.)
